I was having the same issue @paviad and @davidgrenier were having, and after a short bit of digging it seems the that StTable search mechanism will treat falsey search values as null. See [the search function at the time of this comment](https://github.com/lorenzofox3/Smart-Table/blob/31189378ac6bc2763ea472eec2fb99d761ed9f77/src/stTable.js#L108).

Searching with a string 'false' will show only rows whos predicate matches `false` or `'false'`.

```javascript
.directive('stCheck', function () {
  return {
    restrict: 'E',
    scope: {
      predicate: '@'
    },
    require: '^stTable',
    template: '<input type="checkbox" data-ng-model="sel" ng-change="stCheckChange()"> ',
    link: function (scope, element, attr, ctrl) {
      scope.stCheckChange = function stCheckChange() {
        if (scope.sel) {
          ctrl.search(scope.sel, scope.predicate);
        } else {
          // SmartTable search mechanism will throw out the search term if it is falsey
          ctrl.search('false', scope.predicate);
        }
      };
    }
  };
})
```

FYI, the above doesn't entirely work if there is a custom directive on a table column (i.e. for a column that is "true" I'm displaying a green checkmark, for "false" nothing).  While the underlying arrays are updated correctly, the displayed results (formatting) is not.  There's two ways you can do it...

1) Reset the displayedData (this will force the current display to refresh)

        $scope.$on('setAuthorization', function (event, data) {
            angular.forEach($scope.usersData, function (u, i) {
                if (u.Id === data.UserId) {
                    $scope.usersData[i].IsAuthorized = data.IsAuthorized;
                }
            });

            $scope.displayedData = angular.copy($scope.displayedData);
        });

This way I'm only copying the displayed data and not the *entire* collection.

2) Use a directive on the column:

    mc.directive('csBoolean', function ($compile) {
        return {
            require: '^stTable',
            scope: {
                row: '=csBoolean'
            },
            link: function (scope, element) {
                scope.$watch('row.IsAuthorized', function (value) {
                    if (value)
                        element.html('<i class="fa fa-check fa-2x green"></i>');
                    else
                        element.html('<span />');
                });
            }
        }
    });

With my table row having:

    <td cs-boolean="row" class="text-center"></td>

If I use the second approach, I don't need the following line in my above code as the watcher will update the column's view:

            $scope.displayedData = angular.copy($scope.displayedData);

