@PabloLefort I'm not sure it would increase the coverage.

Coverage is just a tool verifying that every line of code is executed. So to increase coverage you will need to make sure the test you write execute the lines of code you added. It means that you will have to `send` a byte object.

Also because your code will only ever be executed on Python 3, you won't be able to increase Python 2's coverage. But that's okay, I'll merge it if Python 3 pass coverage test.

It seems these are for parameters not used in the calculation of the loss function. Here is a minimal example. The first causes a problem with both SimpleExecutionEngine and BatchedExecutionEngine because it is simply adding a parameter node after the final loss is computed. The second causes a problem only with the BatchedExecutionEngine. It's more subtle: The lookup parameter is added before the loss, but it's batchable, which means it is executed last, and therefore the "loss" batch is lower than the parameter batch, causing problems:

// Causes crash in both SimpleExecutionEngine and BatchedExecutionEngine
void ParameterAfterLossBug() {
	ComputationGraph cg;
	Model model;
	Parameter param = model.add_parameters({ 1 });

	Expression loss = zeroes(cg, { 1 });
	Expression p = parameter(cg, param);

	cg.incremental_forward(loss);
	cg.backward(loss);
}

// Causes crash only in BatchedExecutionEngine
//  - The problem is that the lookup operation is batchable, so is done after all other operations. 
//  - As a result, the finalLoss batch is lower than the lookup batch.
void BatchedParameterAfterLossBug() {
	ComputationGraph cg;
	Model model;
	LookupParameter param = model.add_lookup_parameters(10, { 1 });

	Expression p = lookup(cg, param, 1);
	Expression loss = zeroes(cg, { 1 });

	cg.incremental_forward(loss);
	cg.backward(loss);
}

@fungi I believe the reason that I dropped checking for `project_urls` because [PEP 345](https://www.python.org/dev/peps/pep-0345/#requires-python) specifies that both `Requires-Python` and `Project-URL` are required, and so anything using version >= 1.2 *must* have `Requires-Python`.

That said, this is a heuristic based on metadata generated mostly from `setup()`, so probably the original checking for "if you request *any* features of 1.2, we should create a valid version 1.2+ file".

So it was intentional but probably wrong. Feel free to make a PR to add it back.

