@AcckiyGerman 
`"title": "мамы"` and `"title": "\u043c\u0430\u043c\u044b"` are equivalent, both decode to exactly the same thing and are both valid under the JSON standard (as ASCII is a subset of UTF-8).
The latter is more compatible with transports which prefer ASCII only (e.g. emails...). Why is this important?

@bbangert - good points...  I was kind of relying on #190 as being a reason that we should support preparers without really thinking of a good use-case for having that.  Also, I was going towards the "deserialize(serialize())" because Cornice is actually already doing that in some places (https://github.com/mozilla-services/cornice/blob/master/cornice/schemas.py#L137) but just not consistently.

However, iterating over everything to apply `str()` to it is pretty much the same thing as calling colander's `serialize()` except that it will ignore `default` and `preparer`.  I don't think you can improve speed by testing if the value is already a string over just calling str() on everything (I haven't tested that assumption, though).

I was also leaning towards just letting colander handle as much as possible as it's already well tested.

